"'''Break It Off'''" is a song by [[Barbadian people|Barbadian]] recording artist [[Rihanna]] from her second studio album, ''[[A Girl Like Me (Rihanna album)|A Girl Like Me]]'' (2006). It was written by [[Sean Paul]], Donovan Bennett, K. Ford and Rihanna, while production was handled by Don Corleon. The song was released on November 13, 2006, as the album's fourth and final single. "Break It Off" is a futuristic [[Pop music|pop]]-[[dancehall]] song, which is layered over an [[Electropop|electro]]-[[reggae]] [[Beat (music)|beat]]. Critical reception of the song was positive, with reviewers praising the collaboration between Rihanna and Paul and as a return to the former's roots. "Break It Off" made chart appearances on the singles charts of the United States and Belgium. It peaked at number nine on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart and number six on the [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)|Pop Songs]] chart. In the [[Flanders, Belgium|Flanders region of Belgium]], it peaked at number 10. Rihanna performed the song at [[Radio One Big Weekend]] in 2007 and it was included on the [[set list]] of her [[Good Girl Gone Bad Tour]] (2007<U+2013>09), and was subsequently included on the accompanying DVD release, entitled ''[[Good Girl Gone Bad Live]]''.

==Background and release==
[[File:SeanPaulIRAWA.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.75|alt=A picture of a man wearing a beige jacket and holding a silver award statue|[[Sean Paul]] co-wrote "Break It Off" and appeared as a featured vocalist.]]
"Break It Off" was recorded at 2 Hard Studios in [[Kingston, Jamaica]].<ref name="Notes"/> It was written by Donovan Bennett, Sean Paul Henriques (better known as [[Sean Paul]]), K. Ford and [[Rihanna]], who is credited as Robyn Fenty.<ref name="Notes"/> Production of the song was handled by Don Corleon.<ref name="Notes"/> It was [[Music engineer|engineered]] by Jeremy Harding and Bennett, who also [[Mixing (music production)|mixed]] the song.<ref name="Notes"/> All [[instrumentation]] was provided by Bennett.<ref name="Notes"/> Paul explained how he and Rihanna met in a 2011 interview with ''[[Rap-Up]]''. During her visit to Jamaica, Rihanna was taken on a tour around the island by Paul, where he took her to some of the beaches and experienced the nightlife.<ref name="2RapUp2011">{{cite web|title=Rap-Up TV: Sean Paul gets 'Deep' with Kelly Rowland, reminisces about Rihanna, & praises Nicki Minaj|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/10/13/rap-up-tv-sean-paul-gets-deep-with-kelly-rowland-reminisces-about-rihanna-praises-nicki-minaj/|work=[[Rap-Up]]|publisher=Devin Lazerine|date=August 5, 2012|accessdate=August 5, 2012}}</ref> He continued to explain that they spent a few days together and that he took her to the [[Bob Marley Museum]], which was something she had "always wanted to do."<ref name="2RapUp2011"/> Reminiscing on "Break It Off" and Rihanna, Paul stated that working with the singer and creating the song was "his most memorable collaboration."<ref name="2RapUp2011"/> "Break It Off" was released as the fourth and final single from Rihanna's second studio album, ''[[A Girl like Me (Rihanna album)|A Girl like Me]]'' (2006). It was released to US [[Contemporary hit radio]] station playlists on November 13, 2006, by [[Def Jam Recordings]].<ref name="USRadioRelease">{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239|title=Available for aiplay|publisher=[[FMQB]]|date=August 8, 2006|accessdate=December 11, 2011}}</ref> It was also made available to [[Music download|download digitally]] via [[iTunes Store|iTunes]] in various countries around the world on February 27, 2007, including Australia,<ref name="AustraliaiTunes">{{cite web|url=http://itunes.apple.com/au/album/break-it-off-single/id218285244|title=Break It Off <U+2013> Single <U+2013> Rihanna & Sean Paul|work=''[[iTunes Store]] (Australia)''|publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=August 5, 2012}}</ref> Austria,<ref name="AustriaTunes">{{cite web|url=http://itunes.apple.com/at/album/break-it-off-single/id218285244|title=Break It Off <U+2013> Single <U+2013> Rihanna & Sean Paul|work=''iTunes Store (Austria)''|publisher=Apple|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=August 5, 2012|language=German}}</ref> Belgium<ref name="BelgiumiTunes">{{cite web|url=http://itunes.apple.com/be/album/break-it-off-single/id218285244|title=Break It Off <U+2013> Single <U+2013> Rihanna & Sean Paul|work=''iTunes Store (Belgium)''|publisher=Apple|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=August 5, 2012}}</ref> and Spain.<ref name="SpainiTunes">{{cite web|url=http://itunes.apple.com/es/album/break-it-off-single/id218285244|title=Break It Off <U+2013> Single <U+2013> Rihanna & Sean Paul|work=''iTunes Store (Spain)''|publisher=Apple|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=August 5, 2012|language=Spanish}}</ref>

==Composition and lyrics==
"Break It Off" is a futuristic<ref name="About.com"/> [[Pop music|pop]]-[[dancehall]] song, which is layered over an [[Electropop|electro]]-[[reggae]] [[Beat (music)|beat]].<ref name="NYTReview"/> It received a comparison by Ruth Jamieson for ''[[The Guardian]]'' to Rihanna's debut single "[[Pon de Replay]]" from her first studio album, ''[[Music of the Sun]]''.<ref name="The Guardian">{{cite news|last=Jamieson|first=Ruth|title=Rihanna, A Girl Like Me|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2006/apr/23/34|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=April 23, 2006|accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref> According to Dan Charnas for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', "Break It Off" showcases Rihanna's [[Caribbean]] roots.<ref name="TWPReview">{{cite news|last=Charnas|first=Dan|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/25/AR2006042501896.html|title=Quick Spin|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|date=April 25, 2006|accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref> "We Ride" is written in the [[key (music)|key]] of [[D-flat major|D major]] and is set in [[common time]] with a moderate dance [[tempo|groove]] with 130 [[Beats per minute#Beats per minute|beats per minute]] (BPM).<ref name="Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna Break It Off">{{cite web|url=|title=Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna 'Break It Off'|work=''Musicnotes.com''|publisher=[[Peer International (music publishing)|Peer International Music Publishing]]|year=2006}}</ref> Rihanna's [[vocal range]] in the song spans one [[octave]] from the lower note of [[A (musical note)|A<sub>3</sub>]] to the higher note of [[A (musical note)|A<sub>4</sub>]].<ref name="Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna Break It Off"/> The song includes [[piano]] keys and [[guitar]] strings as part of its instrumental composition.<ref name="Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna Break It Off"/><ref name="Notes"/>

==Critical reception==
"Break It Off" garnered a positive response from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. David Jeffries for [[AllMusic]] was complimentary of "Break It Off", writing that it is "totally juiced" and that she provides good competition for Paul.<ref name="AllmusicReview">{{cite web|last=Jeffries|first=David|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-girl-like-me-r828728/review|title=Review: A Girl Like Me|work=''[[AllMusic]]''|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref> Kelefa Sanneh for ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the song, and described it as Rihanna's "triumphant return to her old formula."<ref name="NYTReview">{{cite news|last=Sanneh|first=Kelefa|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9403E2DD123FF937A15757C0A9609C8B63|title=Critic's Choice: New CD's|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, Jr.]]|date=April 24, 2006|accessdate=August 5, 2012}}</ref> Quentin B. Huff for [[PopMatters]] lauded Sean Paul for his contribution to the song while praising Rihanna's hook, writing that "[Rihanna's] hook is so infectious that hers is the voice you ultimately remember. That's another dancehall-flavored song and another winner."<ref name="PopMattersReview">{{cite web|last=Huff|first=Quentin B.|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/rihanna-a-girl-like-me/|title=Review: A Girl Like Me|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|date=April 25, 2006|accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref> Bill Lamb for [[About.com]] called "Break It Off", along with "Kisses Don't Lie", "candidates for widespread pop radio airplay".<ref name="About.com">{{cite web|last=Lamb|first=Bill|url=http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/rihannagirllike.htm|title=Rihanna <U+2013> A Girl Like Me|work=''[[About.com]]''|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>

==Chart performance==
"Break It Off" debuted at number 40 on the US [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)|Pop Songs]] chart in the issue dated November 18, 2006.<ref name="USPopDebut40">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/charts/pop-songs?chartDate=2006-11-18&order=gainer|title=Pop Songs: Week of November 18, 2006|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=November 18, 2006|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> The following week, it ascended to number 35,<ref name="USPopSecond25">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/charts/pop-songs?chartDate=2006-11-25&order=gainer|title=Pop Songs: Week of November 25, 2006|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=November 25, 2006|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> and again to number 32 in its third week on the chart.<ref name="USPopThird32/Fourth28">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/charts/pop-songs?chartDate=2006-11-25&order=gainer|title=Pop Songs: Week of December 9, 2006|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=December 9, 2006|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> "Break It Off" climbed into the top 30 at number 28 in its fourth week on December 9, 2006,<ref name="USPopThird32/Fourth28"/> and to number 25 in its fifth week.<ref name="USPopFifth25">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/charts/pop-songs?chartDate=2006-12-16&order=gainer|title=Pop Songs: Week of December 16, 2006|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=December 16, 2006|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> On December 23, 2006, the song climbed again to number 21,<ref name="USPopSixth21">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/charts/pop-songs?chartDate=2006-12-23&order=gainer|title=Pop Songs: Week of December 23, 2006|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=December 23, 2006|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> and reached its 2006 peak of number 16 on December 30, 2006.<ref name="USPopSeventh16">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/charts/pop-songs?chartDate=2006-12-30&order=gainer|title=Pop Songs: Week of December 30, 2006|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=December 30, 2006|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> In the first chart issue of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' in January 2007, "Break It Off" charted at number 14.<ref name="USPopEight14">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/charts/pop-songs?chartDate=2007-01-06&order=gainer|title=Pop Songs: Week of January 6, 2007|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=January 6, 2007|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> It broke into the top 10 on February 3, 2007,<ref name="USPopTwelth10">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/charts/pop-songs?chartDate=2007-01-06&order=gainer|title=Pop Songs: Week of February 3, 2007|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=February 3, 2007|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> and ascended to number seven the following week.<ref name="USPopThirteenth7">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/charts/pop-songs?chartDate=2007-02-10|title=Pop Songs: Week of February 10, 2007|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=February 10, 2007|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> "Break It Off" peaked at number six on February 24, 2007.<ref name="USPopFifteenth6">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/charts/pop-songs?chartDate=2007-02-24|title=Pop Songs: Week of February 24, 2007|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=February 24, 2007|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> The song remained on the Pop Songs chart for a total of 22 weeks.<ref name="USPopDuration">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/song/rihanna-sean-paul/break-it-off/8177223|title=Rihanna <U+2013> Pop Songs Chart History|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=February 24, 2007|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> On December 9, 2006, "Break It Off" debuted on the US  [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart at number 95.<ref name="USHot100Debut95">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100#/charts/hot-100?chartDate=2006-12-09&order=gainer|title=Hot 100: Week of December 9, 2006|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=December 9, 2006|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> The song climbed to number 52 on March 3, 2007, and surged 42 chart positions to number 10 the following week.<ref name="USHotTwelth52/Thirteenth10">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100#/charts/hot-100?chartDate=2007-03-10|title=Hot 100: Week of March 3, 2007|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=March 3, 2007|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> In its fourteenth week on the chart, the song peaked at number nine, and was awarded with the Digital Gainer honor.<ref name="USHotPeak9">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100#/charts/hot-100?chartDate=2007-03-17|title=Hot 100: Week of March 17, 2007|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=March 17, 2007|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> On March 24, 2007, the song debuted and peaked at number 10 in the Flanders region of Belgium.<ref name="BelgiumPeak">{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Rihanna+%26+Sean+Paul&titel=Break+It+Off&cat=s|title=Rihanna & Sean Paul<U+2013> Break It Off|work=''ultratop.be/nl''|publisher=Hung Medien|date=March 24, 2007|accessdate=April 28, 2012|language=Dutch}}</ref>

==Live performances==
Rihanna performed the song as part of a [[set list]] at [[Radio One Big Weekend]] in 2007.<ref name="ROBW2007">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/bigweekend/2007/artists/rihanna/|title=Rihanna: Sunday <U+2013> Main Stage|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=August 5, 2012}}</ref> The set consisted of "Pon de Replay", "Break It Off", "[[SOS (Rihanna song)|SOS]]", "[[Breakin' Dishes]]", "[[Unfaithful (Rihanna song)|Unfaithful]]", "[[Shut Up and Drive (Rihanna song)|Shut Up and Drive]]" and "[[Umbrella (song)|Umbrella]]".<ref name="ROBW2007"/> "Break It Off" was also included on the set list of Rihanna's [[Good Girl Gone Bad Tour]] (2007<U+2013>09), and was later included on the DVD release, entitled ''[[Good Girl Gone Bad Live]]''.<ref name="GGGBL">{{cite web|url=http://itunes.apple.com/ar/album/good-girl-gone-bad-live/id283129314|title=Good Girl Gone Bad (Live) <U+2013> Rihanna|work=''iTunes Store (Argentina)''|publisher=Apple|date=June 16, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2012|langiahe=Portugese}}</ref>

